I have everything I need. The diagnosis is clear. Here is the complete analysis and fix.

---

## Diagnosis

The bug is in **`src/app/(frontend)/(site)/layout.module.scss`**. The `@media (pointer: fine) and (max-width: …)` block correctly puts `min-width: $elan-bp-sm` (672px) on `.contentAreaInner` and `overflow-x: auto` on `.contentArea` — that part is right. But the bug exists **outside** that media query: `.siteWrapper` has no `min-width`, and the `<nav>` inside it uses `position: sticky` — which is not `fixed`. That means the nav scrolls with the document.

Wait — re-reading the user report: *"the fixed nav"*. Let me re-examine what `position: sticky` does at sub-320px. The nav is `sticky`, not `fixed`. The issue isn't that the nav is `position: fixed` — it's that the `.navInner` has `max-width: $elan-container-wide` (1440px) with `margin: 0 auto`, but more importantly:

The real culprit is **`max-width: $elan-container-wide`** on `.navInner` combined with `padding` — but at under 320px, the nav itself has **no minimum width** and no overflow containment. The `.navInner` content (logo + links) can't compress below its intrinsic width, so it overflows the `<nav>` — but because the `<nav>` is a sibling of `.contentArea` (not inside it), it sits outside the `overflow-x: auto` scroll container. The browser's document-level scroll is therefore suppressed by something setting `overflow-x` at a higher level.

The smoking gun: **`body` or `html` implicitly get `overflow-x: hidden`** as a side-effect of a child element overflowing without a proper scroll container ancestor — but more precisely, the `.siteWrapper` `display: flex; flex-direction: column` wrapper has no `overflow-x` declaration. When `.navInner`'s content exceeds the nav width, the overflow bleeds into the flex column, widens `.siteWrapper`, and since `.siteWrapper` has no `overflow-x: auto`, the browser treats the page root as the scroll container — but the nav being `sticky` means it re-anchors to the viewport edge, not to the scrolled content position, cutting off the right side.

**Root cause:** AP-067 — *Min-Width Floor on a Root Wrapper That Contains Functional Chrome*. The `.navInner` has a `max-width` centering wrapper but the nav's flex content (logo + links) has no `min-width` floor and no overflow containment at the nav level. Below ~260px the nav's intrinsic content width exceeds the viewport, the overflow propagates to the document, and because the nav is `sticky` (viewport-anchored), it paints at viewport width while the page's horizontal extent is wider — making the right portion of the nav unreachable. The `overflow-x: auto` is only on `.contentArea`, leaving the nav in a scroll-dead zone.

---

## Root Cause

**AP-067: Min-Width Floor on a Root Wrapper That Contains Functional Chrome.**

The existing design correctly avoids putting `min-width` on `.siteWrapper` — that was the lesson from FB-147/FB-149. But the fix left a gap: it never added overflow protection at the **`.siteWrapper`** level. When nav content overflows the viewport below ~260px, there is no `overflow-x` on `.siteWrapper` to contain it. The `sticky` nav paints within the viewport while the document overflow is wider, making the right edge of the nav unreachable. You cannot scroll to it because the nav is out of the `overflow-x: auto` scroll region entirely.

---

## Fix

Three files change. One new anti-pattern entry. One responsive-doc amendment.

### 1. `src/app/(frontend)/(site)/layout.module.scss`

The fix has two parts:
- Add `overflow-x: clip` to `.siteWrapper` — this prevents the nav's intrinsic-content overflow from widening the document without creating a scroll container (unlike `hidden`, `clip` does not establish a new formatting context that would trap `sticky` positioning).
- Add `min-width: min-content` to the `.nav`-level rule so the nav's content never forces a wider document than necessary.

Since we don't own `.nav` in this file (it lives in `Navigation.module.scss`), the second part goes there instead. But the primary fix is in the layout.

```scss
// src/app/(frontend)/(site)/layout.module.scss

@use '../../../styles' as *;

// ── ZERO RADIUS OVERRIDE ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────
// Portfolio branding: all border-radius is 0 on the public site.
// ...existing comment unchanged...

.siteWrapper {
  min-height: 100vh;
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: column;
  // Prevent nav or footer intrinsic-content overflow from widening the document
  // at sub-360px viewports. `overflow-x: clip` is used instead of `hidden`
  // because `hidden` would create a new stacking context that breaks
  // `position: sticky` on the nav. `clip` cuts overflow geometrically
  // without affecting stacking or scroll containment. See AP-067.
  overflow-x: clip;

  --portfolio-radius-xs: 0;
  --portfolio-radius-sm: 0;
  --portfolio-radius-md: 0;
  --portfolio-radius-lg: 0;
  --portfolio-radius-xl: 0;
  --portfolio-radius-2xl: 0;
}

.contentArea {
  flex: 1;
  position: relative;
  z-index: 1;
  min-width: 0;
}

.contentAreaInner {
  // Default: no width constraint — content fills contentArea naturally.
}

// ── DESKTOP MIN-WIDTH FLOOR (CONTENT ONLY) ────────────────────────────────
// ...existing comment unchanged...
@media (pointer: fine) and (max-width: #{$elan-bp-sm - 1px}) {
  .contentArea {
    overflow-x: auto;
  }

  .contentAreaInner {
    min-width: $elan-bp-sm;
  }
}
```

**Full replacement file:**

```scss
@use '../../../styles' as *;

// ── ZERO RADIUS OVERRIDE ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────
// Portfolio branding: all border-radius is 0 on the public site.
// This overrides CSS custom properties so DS components (Badge, Card, Input,
// Dialog, Tooltip, etc.) all render with sharp corners when inside the (site)
// route group. Structural exceptions (Avatar, Toggle, Slider, ProgressBar)
// restore their radius locally in their own SCSS modules.
// See docs/design/branding.md §1 for the full rule.

.siteWrapper {
  min-height: 100vh;
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: column;
  // Prevent nav / footer intrinsic-content overflow from widening the
  // document at sub-360px viewports. `overflow-x: clip` is used instead of
  // `overflow-x: hidden` because `hidden` establishes a new block formatting
  // context that breaks `position: sticky` on the nav child. `clip` cuts
  // overflow geometrically without creating a scroll container or altering
  // stacking context — sticky positioning is preserved. See AP-067.
  overflow-x: clip;

  --portfolio-radius-xs: 0;
  --portfolio-radius-sm: 0;
  --portfolio-radius-md: 0;
  --portfolio-radius-lg: 0;
  --portfolio-radius-xl: 0;
  --portfolio-radius-2xl: 0;
  // --portfolio-radius-full is intentionally NOT overridden.
  // Structural exceptions (Avatar, Toggle, Slider, ProgressBar) depend on it
  // for circular shapes. Badge pill shape should not be used on the portfolio —
  // always pass shape="squared" per docs/design/branding.md §1.2.
}

.contentArea {
  flex: 1;
  position: relative;
  z-index: 1;
  // Allow the flex child to shrink below its intrinsic min content width so
  // the overflow scroll container below can take effect at narrow viewports.
  min-width: 0;
}

.contentAreaInner {
  // Default: no width constraint — content fills contentArea naturally.
}

// ── DESKTOP MIN-WIDTH FLOOR (CONTENT ONLY) ────────────────────────────────
// Below the sm breakpoint on mouse-driven devices, the page *content* gets a
// 672px floor with horizontal scroll so case studies and other composed
// surfaces render at their intended width. Nav and SiteFooter are siblings
// of `.contentArea`, so they stay fluid to the actual viewport and fall back
// to their mobile layouts — functional chrome must always be reachable and
// readable at any width. Scoped to `pointer: fine` so touch devices (which
// have their own phone composition at any width) are unaffected. See FB-147,
// FB-149 and `docs/design/responsive.md` §6.10.
@media (pointer: fine) and (max-width: #{$elan-bp-sm - 1px}) {
  .contentArea {
    // Contain the horizontal overflow inside `.contentArea` so it does NOT
    // grow the document width — siblings (Nav, SiteFooter) stay at viewport
    // width and remain fully responsive.
    overflow-x: auto;
  }

  .contentAreaInner {
    min-width: $elan-bp-sm;
  }
}
```

### 2. `src/components/ui/Navigation/Navigation.module.scss`

The nav's inner wrapper needs a `min-width: min-content` so it never forces a document width wider than its own content — this is a secondary defensive measure that ensures the nav advertises its true minimum need to the browser layout engine, preventing phantom overflow on sub-260px viewports even if the `clip` on `.siteWrapper` is ever relaxed.

Add one line to `.navInner`:

```diff
 .navInner {
   display: flex;
   align-items: center;
   justify-content: space-between;
   max-width: $elan-container-wide;
+  min-width: min-content;
   margin: 0 auto;
   padding: var(--portfolio-spacer-1-5x) var(--portfolio-spacer-2x);

   @media #{$elan-mq-sm} {
     padding: var(--portfolio-spacer-1-5x) var(--portfolio-spacer-4x);
   }
 }
```

### 3. `docs/design-anti-patterns.md` — update AP-067

The existing AP-067 entry documents the FB-147/FB-149 lesson (don't put `min-width` on the root wrapper). It needs a new **amended** clause covering the `overflow-x: clip` vs `overflow-x: hidden` distinction on sticky-containing wrappers. Append the following block to the existing AP-067 entry:

```markdown
---

<a id="ap-067"></a>
## AP-067: Min-Width Floor on a Root Wrapper That Contains Functional Chrome

**Status: ACTIVE**
**Last amended: 2025-XX-XX (FB-NNN: sub-320px nav clip regression)**

**Trigger:** Setting `min-width` on `.siteWrapper` (or any ancestor that contains
both `position: sticky` chrome and page content) to prevent the desktop layout
from collapsing at narrow viewports.

**Why it's wrong:** A `min-width` on the page root widens the *document* — not
just the content. Because the nav is `position: sticky` (viewport-anchored), it
paints at viewport width. When the document is wider than the viewport, the
right side of the nav is clipped and unreachable — there is no horizontal scroll
that encompasses it. The user literally cannot access nav items on the right.

**Second failure mode — `overflow-x: hidden` on a sticky-child wrapper:**
Using `overflow-x: hidden` to suppress the overflow instead also breaks
`position: sticky`. `hidden` establishes a new block formatting context (BFC)
which becomes the scroll container for its descendants — sticky children
within it anchor to the BFC boundary, not the viewport, so they stop behaving
as sticky nav items.

**Correct alternative:**
1. **Content only gets the floor.** Apply `min-width` exclusively to
   `.contentAreaInner`. The scroll container (`overflow-x: auto`) wraps only
   `.contentArea`, not `.siteWrapper` or `body`.
2. **Use `overflow-x: clip` on `.siteWrapper`**, never `overflow-x: hidden`.
   `clip` cuts overflow geometrically without establishing a BFC or scroll
   container — `position: sticky` continues to anchor to the viewport.
3. **Never set `min-width` on `html`, `body`, or `.siteWrapper`.**

```css
/* ✗ Wrong — widens the document, clips sticky nav */
.siteWrapper { min-width: 320px; }

/* ✗ Wrong — breaks sticky positioning */
.siteWrapper { overflow-x: hidden; }

/* ✓ Correct */
.siteWrapper  { overflow-x: clip; }          /* geometry cut, no BFC */
.contentArea  { overflow-x: auto; min-width: 0; } /* scroll container, content only */
.contentAreaInner { min-width: 672px; }      /* floor on content, not chrome */
```

**Related:** FB-147, FB-149, `docs/design/responsive.md` §6.10
**Frustration count:** 3 rounds across 3 sessions.
```

### 4. `docs/design-feedback-log.md` — append FB-151

Prepend to the top of the active feedback log:

```markdown
#### FB-151: "On viewports narrower than 320px the entire page stops scrolling horizontally — the nav is clipped on the right"

**UX Intent:** Functional chrome (nav) must be reachable at *any* viewport width. If a user can hover over a nav item but cannot scroll to click it, the site is broken regardless of how niche the viewport is.
**Root Cause:** `.siteWrapper` had no `overflow-x` declaration. Below ~260px the nav's intrinsic content width (logo + tagline) exceeded the viewport, widening the document. The `overflow-x: auto` scroll container existed only on `.contentArea` — the nav, as a sibling, was outside it. Because the nav is `position: sticky`, it painted at viewport width while the scroll extent was wider, making its right edge permanently unreachable. AP-067.
**Resolution:** Added `overflow-x: clip` to `.siteWrapper` (not `hidden` — `hidden` would break sticky). Added `min-width: min-content` to `.navInner` as a secondary defensive measure. AP-067 amended with the `clip` vs `hidden` distinction.
**Pattern extracted → `design-anti-patterns.md` AP-067 (amended), `design/responsive.md` §6.10**
```

---

## Why `overflow-x: clip` and Not `overflow-x: hidden`

This is the critical nuance the rule must encode:

| Property | Creates BFC? | Breaks `sticky`? | Cuts overflow? |
|---|---|---|---|
| `overflow-x: hidden` | **Yes** | **Yes** — sticky anchors to the BFC, not viewport | Yes |
| `overflow-x: clip` | **No** | **No** — no scroll container created | Yes |
| `overflow-x: auto` | Yes | Yes — only use on non-sticky-ancestor containers | Only when needed |

`clip` was introduced precisely for this use case: geometric overflow cutting without any of the formatting-context side-effects of `hidden`. It has [full modern browser support](https://caniuse.com/mdn-css_properties_overflow_clip).

---

## Principle

**AP-067 (amended):** Never set `min-width` on `html`, `body`, or any wrapper that contains `position: sticky` functional chrome. The scroll container for the desktop floor (`overflow-x: auto`) must wrap only page **content** (`.contentArea`/`.contentAreaInner`), never the full document shell. When you need to cut overflow on a sticky-containing ancestor, use `overflow-x: clip` — it performs geometric clipping without establishing a block formatting context, leaving sticky anchoring intact. `overflow-x: hidden` on such a wrapper is equally wrong: it breaks sticky positioning while appearing to fix the overflow symptom.
